quran[8]{c,v,t,f}:
33,55,"It will not be blameworthy for the wives of the Prophet if their fathers, their sons, their brothers, their brothers' sons, their sisters' sons, {1} and the women with whom they have social relations, {2} and the persons whom their right hands possess enter their houses. {3} (O women), shun disobeying Allah. Allah is watchful over everything. {4}",footnotes:1:For explanation
33,56,"Allah and His angels bless the Prophet. {1} Believers, invoke blessings and peace on him. {2}",footnotes:1:In other words
33,57,"Verily those who cause annoyance to Allah and His Messenger � Allah has cursed them in this world and in the Hereafter and has prepared for them a humiliating chastisement. {1}",footnotes:1:“To cause harm to Allah” implies two things: That Allah should be disobeyed
33,58,"Those who cause hurt to believing men and to believing women have invited upon themselves a calumny {1} and a manifest sin.",footnotes:1:This verse determines the definition of slander. It is to ascribe a fault to a person which he does not have
33,59,"O Prophet, enjoin your wives and your daughters and the believing women, to draw a part of their outer coverings around them. {1} It is likelier that they will be recognised and not molested. {2} Allah is Most Forgiving, Most Merciful. {3}",footnotes:1:Jilbab is a large sheet and adna is to draw close and wrap up
33,60,"If the hypocrites and those in whose hearts there is a sickness, {1} and the scandal mongers in Madinah {2} do not desist from their vile acts, We shall urge you to take action against them, and then they will hardly be able to stay in the city with you.",footnotes:1:“Having diseased hearts” points to two kinds of evils:(1) That a person should be an ill-wisher of Islam and the Muslims although he gets himself counted among the Muslims; and
33,61,"They shall be cursed from all around and they shall be ruthlessly killed wherever they are seized."
33,62,"This has been Allah's Way with those who have gone before, and you shall find no change in Allah's Way. {1}",footnotes:1:That is
